  <h1>ITR filing due dates FY 2026-27 (AY 2027-28)</h1>
  <div class="byline">
    <span class="av">SR</span><b>Written by a Chartered Accountant</b>
    <span class="sep"></span><span>NumberIQ Editorial</span>
    <span class="sep"></span><span>Last reviewed June 2026</span>
    <span class="sep"></span><span>5 min read</span>
  </div>
</header>
<div class="divide"></div>

<article class="prose read">
  <p class="answer-first lead"><b>For FY 2026-27 (AY 2027-28), the ITR due date is 31 July 2027 for taxpayers not requiring audit, 31 October 2027 for audit cases, and 30 November 2027 for taxpayers with transfer-pricing obligations.</b> A belated or revised return can be filed up to 31 December 2027.</p>

  <div class="toc"><b>On this page</b><a href="#s0">The main due dates</a> &middot; <a href="#s1">Belated, revised and updated returns</a> &middot; <a href="#s2">Late filing costs</a> &middot; <a href="#s3">Plan the filing</a></div>

  <!-- ADSENSE SLOT 1 — activate after approval -->

  <h2 id="s0">The main due dates</h2>
<div class="table-wrap"><table><thead><tr><th>Taxpayer</th><th>Due date (AY 2027-28)</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Individuals/HUF not under audit</td><td>31 July 2027</td></tr><tr><td>Taxpayers requiring tax audit</td><td>31 October 2027</td></tr><tr><td>Tax audit report (3CA/3CB-3CD)</td><td>30 September 2027</td></tr><tr><td>Transfer-pricing cases (Form 3CEB)</td><td>30 November 2027</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>Dates are subject to extension by the CBDT. <span class="verify">VERIFY</span> any notified extension for the year.</p>

  <h2 id="s1">Belated, revised and updated returns</h2>
<ul><li><b>Belated/revised return:</b> up to 31 December 2027 (with a late fee under Section 234F for belated returns).</li><li><b>Updated return (ITR-U):</b> can be filed within the extended window from the end of the assessment year, on payment of additional tax. <span class="verify">VERIFY</span> the current ITR-U time limit and rates.</li></ul>

  <h2 id="s2">Late filing costs</h2>
<p>Filing after the due date attracts a fee under <b>Section 234F</b> (Rs.5,000, reduced to Rs.1,000 where total income is up to Rs.5 lakh) and interest under <a href="../interest-234abc-calculator.html">Section 234A</a> on unpaid tax. Certain losses cannot be carried forward if the return is filed late &mdash; see <a href="set-off-carry-forward-losses-income-tax.html">set-off and carry-forward</a>.</p>

  <h2 id="s3">Plan the filing</h2>
<ul><li>Reconcile <a href="form-26as-ais-tis-difference.html">26AS/AIS/TIS</a> before filing to avoid mismatches.</li><li>Choose the <a href="old-vs-new-tax-regime-fy2026-27.html">regime</a> and, for business income, file Form 10-IEA in time.</li><li>Verify the return within the prescribed period, or it is treated as not filed.</li></ul>

  <div class="faq">
    <h2 id="faq">Frequently asked questions</h2>
    <details><summary>What is the ITR due date for FY 2026-27?</summary><p>31 July 2027 for non-audit taxpayers, 31 October 2027 for audit cases, and 30 November 2027 for transfer-pricing cases, subject to CBDT extension.</p></details>
    <details><summary>Till when can I file a belated return?</summary><p>Up to 31 December 2027 for AY 2027-28, with a late fee under Section 234F and interest under Section 234A on any unpaid tax.</p></details>
    <details><summary>What is the late filing fee?</summary><p>Under Section 234F, Rs.5,000, reduced to Rs.1,000 where total income does not exceed Rs.5 lakh.</p></details>
  </div>

  <!-- ADSENSE SLOT 2 — activate after approval -->

  <div class="key-takeaways"><h2>Key takeaways</h2>
    <ul><li>Non-audit: 31 July; audit: 31 October; TP: 30 November (AY 2027-28).</li><li>Audit report (3CD) by 30 September.</li><li>Belated/revised return up to 31 December 2027.</li><li>Late filing: Section 234F fee + 234A interest; some losses lapse.</li></ul>
  </div>

